data.content:
**In .NET 11, all your synchronous Cosmos DB calls will throw at runtime — with no opt-in to restore them.** The sync-over-async workaround you had in .NET 10 has been fully removed.

**What breaks:** `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — every sync I/O method on the Cosmos provider.

**Fix:** Convert to async throughout:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

This means callers must also become `async` — the change propagates up the call chain. There is no workaround; the Cosmos SDK is async-only, and EF Core 11 no longer hides that behind sync wrappers.
